{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"033dc7e9-5582-4ddd-95f2-153c3de3a8d5","content":"The project doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- These make it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools (must be an executable).\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5eaf8209-07fb-4fdf-9aad-3e16aad368f4","outputTokens":475,"requestId":"158C:23D333:31E15B5:36928D8:69FBE621"},"id":"493666ea-4143-4d0a-acf8-4496c052ed9b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:08:58.361Z","parentId":"89b64d5c-54f5-4f55-8e5f-0336c40fcaaa"}
